7532	\begin{lemma}
7533	[Push--pull over the {\v C}ech backbone is the product over intersection opens]
7534	  \label{lem:pushPull_sigma_iso}
7535	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.pushPull_sigma_iso}
7536	  \uses{def:push_pull_obj, lem:cech_backbone_left_sigma, lem:coprodPresheafObjIso_mathlib,
7537	    lem:isProductOfDisjoint_mathlib}
7538	  With the notation of Lemma~\ref{lem:cech_backbone_left_sigma}, the push--pull object on
7539	  the degree-\(p\) backbone decomposes as a product over the multi-indices:
7540	  \[
7541	    \operatorname{pushPullObj}\mathcal{F}\,Y_p
7542	      \;\cong\;
7543	    \prod_{\sigma : \mathrm{Fin}(p+1) \to I}
7544	      \operatorname{pushPullObj}\mathcal{F}\,(\operatorname{Over.mk} j_\sigma)
7545	    \qquad \text{in } X.\mathrm{Modules},
7546	  \]
7547	  equivalently \((q_p)_*\,(q_p)^*\mathcal{F} \cong \prod_\sigma (j_\sigma)_*\,
7548	  (j_\sigma)^*\mathcal{F}\).
7549	\end{lemma}
7550	\begin{proof}
7551	  \uses{lem:cech_backbone_left_sigma, lem:coprodPresheafObjIso_mathlib,
7552	    lem:isProductOfDisjoint_mathlib}
7553	  By Lemma~\ref{lem:cech_backbone_left_sigma} the backbone \(Y_p\) is the coproduct
7554	  \(\coprod_\sigma U_\sigma\) with structure map \(q_p = \operatorname{Sigma.desc}(\sigma
7555	  \mapsto j_\sigma)\). A sheaf of modules on a coproduct scheme is the product of its
7556	  restrictions to the components: although the images \(U_\sigma \subseteq X\) overlap, the
7557	  components are \emph{disjoint inside the coproduct space} \(\coprod_\sigma U_\sigma\), so
7558	  the sheaf condition over the disjoint cover by the components expresses the sections over
7559	  any open as the product of the sections over the component traces. Pulling \(\mathcal{F}\)
7560	  back along \(q_p\) and pushing forward therefore yields, componentwise, the push--pull of
7561	  \(\mathcal{F}\) along each \(j_\sigma\).
7562	
7563	  Concretely, build the module-linear comparison map \(\operatorname{pushPullObj}\mathcal{F}\,
7564	  Y_p \to \prod_\sigma \operatorname{pushPullObj}\mathcal{F}\,(\operatorname{Over.mk}
7565	  j_\sigma)\) from the projections induced by the coproduct inclusions \(U_\sigma
7566	  \hookrightarrow Y_p\). To check it is an isomorphism it suffices, since the forgetful
7567	  functor \(\operatorname{Scheme.Modules.toPresheaf}\) is faithful, reflects isomorphisms,
7568	  and preserves limits, to verify the statement on the underlying presheaf of abelian
7569	  groups. There the comparison is the indexed disjoint-union sheaf decomposition: the binary
7570	  case is \(\operatorname{coprodPresheafObjIso}\) of
7571	  Lemma~\ref{lem:coprodPresheafObjIso_mathlib} (sections over a binary coproduct scheme are
7572	  the product of the sections over the two preimages) and, for an abstract sheaf on a space,
7573	  \(\operatorname{isProductOfDisjoint}\) of Lemma~\ref{lem:isProductOfDisjoint_mathlib} (for
7574	  \(U \sqcap V = \bot\), \(F(U \sqcup V) \cong F(U) \times F(V)\)); iterating the binary
7575	  decomposition over the finite index set \(\{\sigma\}\) gives the indexed product.
7576	  Transporting the resulting presheaf isomorphism back through
7577	  \(\operatorname{toPresheaf}\) shows the module-linear comparison is an isomorphism.
7578	\end{proof}
